{
  "title": "2. Input / Output",
  "sections": [

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "1. Definition"
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "text": "Input and Output operations in Python allow interaction between the user and the program. Input is used to take data from the user, while output is used to display results."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 input() is used to take user input\n👉 print() is used to display output\n👉 Input is always taken as string by default"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "2. Input Function"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "The input() function takes input from the user and returns it as a string."
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "Python Input Flow",
      "url": "https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20220803131706/pythoninputoutput.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "name = input(\"Enter your name: \")\nprint(name)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "3. Type Casting in Input"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Since input() returns string, we need type casting for numbers."
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "age = int(input(\"Enter age: \"))\nprice = float(input(\"Enter price: \"))"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "4. Output Function"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "print() function is used to display output on the screen."
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "Python Output Display",
      "url": "https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230607152953/python-functions.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "print(\"Hello World\")\nprint(10)\nprint(\"Age:\", 20)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "5. Formatting Output"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Using comma ( , )",
        "Using + operator",
        "Using f-string (best method)"
      ]
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "name = \"Bhumika\"\nage = 20\n\nprint(\"Name:\", name)\nprint(\"Name: \" + name)\nprint(f\"Name: {name}, Age: {age}\")"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "6. Escape Characters"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "\\n → New line",
        "\\t → Tab space",
        "\\\" → Double quote",
        "\\' → Single quote"
      ]
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "print(\"Hello\\nWorld\")\nprint(\"Hello\\tPython\")"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "7. Taking Multiple Inputs"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "a, b = input(\"Enter two numbers: \").split()\nprint(a, b)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "8. Key Points"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "input() always returns string",
        "Use type casting for numbers",
        "print() is used for output",
        "f-strings are best for formatting",
        "Supports multiple inputs"
      ]
    }

  ]
},

{
  "title": "3. Loops & Conditions",
  "sections": [

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "1. Definition"
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "text": "Loops execute a block of code repeatedly, while conditional statements control the flow of execution based on conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Conditions decide WHAT to execute\n👉 Loops decide HOW MANY TIMES to execute\n👉 Very important for logic building & interviews"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "2. Conditional Statements (if, elif, else)"
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "If-Else Flowchart",
      "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/If-Then-Else-diagram.svg/512px-If-Then-Else-diagram.svg.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 if → checks condition\n👉 elif → multiple conditions\n👉 else → default case"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "marks = 75\n\nif marks >= 90:\n    print(\"Grade A\")\nelif marks >= 60:\n    print(\"Grade B\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Fail\")"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "3. for Loop"
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "For Loop Flow",
      "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/For-loop-diagram.svg/512px-For-loop-diagram.svg.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Used when number of iterations is known\n👉 Works with range(), list, string"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "for i in range(1, 6):\n    print(i)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "4. while Loop"
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "While Loop Flow",
      "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/While-loop-diagram.svg/512px-While-loop-diagram.svg.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Used when condition is important\n👉 Runs until condition becomes False"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "x = 1\nwhile x <= 5:\n    print(x)\n    x += 1"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "5. Loop Control Statements"
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "Break Continue Flow",
      "url": "https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230323181041/Break-and-Continue.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "break → stops loop immediately",
        "continue → skips current iteration",
        "pass → placeholder (does nothing)"
      ]
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "for i in range(5):\n    if i == 3:\n        break\n    print(i)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "6. Nested Loops"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Loop inside another loop\n👉 Used in patterns & matrix problems"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "for i in range(3):\n    for j in range(3):\n        print(i, j)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "7. Key Points"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "if-else controls flow",
        "for loop for fixed iteration",
        "while loop for condition-based iteration",
        "break/continue optimize loops"
      ]
    }

  ]
},

{
  "title": "4. Lists, Tuples, Sets",
  "sections": [

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "1. Definition"
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "text": "Lists, Tuples, and Sets are Python data structures used to store multiple values in a single variable."
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "Python Collections Overview",
      "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Python_collections.svg/512px-Python_collections.svg.png"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "2. List"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Ordered\n👉 Mutable (can change)\n👉 Allows duplicates"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "lst = [10, 20, 30]\nlst.append(40)\nlst[0] = 5\nprint(lst)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "3. Tuple"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Ordered\n👉 Immutable (cannot change)\n👉 Faster than list"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "tup = (1, 2, 3)\nprint(tup)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "4. Set"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Unordered\n👉 No duplicate values\n👉 Fast operations"
    },

    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
