{
  "title": "1. OOP in Python",
  "sections": [

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "1. Definition"
    },
    {
      "type": "definition",
      "text": "Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm based on objects and classes that helps in organizing code in a structured and reusable way."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Used for real-world modeling\n👉 Improves code reusability\n👉 Makes large projects manageable"
    },

    {
      "type": "image",
      "heading": "OOP Concepts Diagram",
      "url": "https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/xBnXKpLZbHLjyZL3VCV2Mpjk_weSkxvECIXv8OXNJEwygT0JLfEe08BnGtN7MwDnBAPW1xlaCk9dKZI3Jig8XBvfXbMYYQaI5QzN5CQA3LJY59jKgp7nBl2nvFP6OEpVG5hiQq2c-wjzvO_H1aGkjcgIIgNCpUqabC5G5scBAeM?purpose=inline"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "2. Class & Object"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Class = blueprint\n👉 Object = real instance"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "class Student:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n\ns1 = Student(\"Bhumika\")\nprint(s1.name)"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "3. Constructor (__init__)"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Automatically called when object is created\n👉 Used to initialize variables"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "4. Encapsulation"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Data hiding using private variables\n👉 Improves security"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "class Bank:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.__balance = 1000\n\n    def get_balance(self):\n        return self.__balance"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "5. Inheritance"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Reuse code from parent class\n👉 Types: Single, Multiple, Multilevel"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "class Animal:\n    def sound(self):\n        print(\"Sound\")\n\nclass Dog(Animal):\n    def bark(self):\n        print(\"Bark\")"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "6. Polymorphism"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Same function behaves differently based on input"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "language": "python",
      "code": "def add(a, b):\n    return a + b"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "7. Abstraction"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "👉 Hide implementation details\n👉 Use abstract classes"
    },

    {
      "type": "heading",
      "heading": "8. Key Points"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "Class = blueprint",
        "Object = instance",
        "Encapsulation = data hiding",
        "Inheritance = reuse",
        "Polymorphism = flexibility",
        "Abstraction = hide complexity"
      ]
    }

  ]
